unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, B, C;

A = (0,0);
B = dir(120);
C = dir(240);

draw(Circle(A,1));
draw(A--B--C--cycle);

label("$0$", A, SE);
label("$z_1$", B, NW);
label("$z_2$", C, SW);
[/asy]

By Vieta's formulas, $z_1 + z_2 = -a$ and $z_1 z_2 = b.$  Then
\begin{align*}
-a &= r \operatorname{cis} \theta + r \operatorname{cis} (\theta + 120^\circ) \\
&= r (\cos \theta + i \sin \theta) + r (\cos (\theta + 120^\circ) + i \sin (\theta + 120^\circ)) \\
&= r \left[ \cos \theta + \cos (\theta + 120^\circ) + i (\sin \theta + \sin (\theta + 120^\circ)) \right] \\
&= r \left[ 2 \cos \left( \frac{\theta + (\theta + 120^\circ)}{2} \right) \cos \left( \frac{\theta - (\theta + 120^\circ)}{2} \right) + 2i \sin \left( \frac{\theta + (\theta + 120^\circ)}{2} \right) \cos \left( \frac{\theta - (\theta + 120^\circ)}{2} \right) \right] \\
&= 2r \cos 60^\circ (\cos \theta - i \sin \theta) \\
&= r (\cos \theta - i \sin \theta) \\
&= r \operatorname{cis} (-\theta),
\end{align*}and
\begin{align*}
b &= r \operatorname{cis} \theta \cdot r \operatorname{cis} (\theta + 120^\circ) \\
&= r^2 \operatorname{cis} (\theta + \theta + 120^\circ) \\
&= r^2 \operatorname{cis} (2 \theta + 120^\circ).
\end{align*}Hence,
\[\frac{a^2}{b} = \frac{r^2 \operatorname{cis} (-2 \theta)}{r^2 \operatorname{cis} (2 \theta + 120^\circ)} = \operatorname{cis} (-2 \theta - 2 \theta - 120^\circ) = \operatorname{cis} (-4 \theta - 120^\circ).\]Since $\theta$ can take on any value, $\frac{a^2}{b}$ can take on any value of the form $\operatorname{cis} \theta.$

Final Answer: $\boxed{\text{Any complex number of the form } \operatorname{cis} \theta}$.

